na where the secular authority did not have the power during the period in question to reject, or even significantly monitor, Inquisitorial trial procedure. It draws upon the detailed testimony to be found in trial transcripts to analyse Jewish interaction with Christian society in an early modern community.This book will appeal to scholars of inquisitorial studies, social and cultural interaction in early modern Europe, Jewish Italian social history and anti-Semitism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArts. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aChristian servants.  aChristian society.  aEstense dukes.  aInquisitorial processi.  aJewish masters.  aJewish offences.  aJews.  aModena.  aPapal Inquisition.  aearly modern Italian duchy.  aearly modern community.  aecclesiastical tribunals.  aseventeenth century Jewish community.1 aAron-Beller, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526151629zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526151629zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526151629/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA